3.0 of 5 bubbles
It's NOT like the pictures
Mar 2012 • Solo
You've seen the picture in the brochure or the site: a beautiful ship sails in lonesome majesty through pristine waters past a series of limestone islands bathed in sunshine under a cloud free blue sky. Well - forget it. It's not going to happen that way. Not unless you are a millionaire, have your own vessel and can manage to convince the other 500 (that’s five HUNDRED) ships that sail Halong Bay to remain in port on “your” day out.
A little background: of the 500 ships approximately 200 are outfitted for overnight cruises, the other 300 do day cruises. On any given day there are approximately 5,000 other tourists who are visiting. Organized one or two overnight tours are sold everywhere in Vietnam. Some tour companies have their own ships and sell direct to the public. Other companies negotiate directly with the ship owners on an individual basis. In both cases the companies then make the tours available to other agents - and it seems like everybody in Vietnam has a tour agency - at a certain price which these agents can then mark up to whatever the traffic will bear. Therefore you will find that exactly the same tour will have very different prices depending on who you buy it from. The overnight tours will have different elements built in - kayaking, visit to a cave, visit to a village, whatever. When comparing prices you must make sure that the prices are for the SAME elements in each case. While clearly taking a tour is the easiest, most convenient way to visit Halong Bay you should keep in mind that you can purchase an eight hour day tour on the dock for $2.
With that background in mind my experience follows.
I purchased my tour through an agency. I wanted to “see” Halong Bay on an overnight and really wasn’t too interested in the elements that made up the package. I paid $110 for a tour on a middle class boat owned by Oriental Sails, a reputable company.
I was picked up promptly at 08:00 at my hotel in a mini van and within 15 minutes we had picked up the other participants at three other hotels and were on our way. It later transpired that three of the people in the van were on another tour run by OS so it seems that pick up was made by hotel location, not tour which is very efficient.
We were accompanied by a representative from OS who gave us a little background and a bottle of water. We then held on for dear life as the driver drove like a bat out of hell passing traffic left, right and center to ensure that we arrived at the dock in time to wait around for half an hour while we got organized. It is 3½ hours from Hanoi to the dock and after an hour a half hour “rest stop” is made to allow you to buy food, gee-gaws (including HUGE concrete statues) and maybe have a suit or other apparel items run up if you failed to buy something in Hoi An. There are also toilets.
So, after four hours, we arrived at the dock along with HORDES (see above) of other tourists. We were then told to wait while the people who were not on “our” tour were shuffled off to join “their” tour and the people who had arrived with another bus or van were joined to our group. A “guide” - I use the term loosely - maybe “minder” would be a more appropriate term - joined us and ushered us down the steep stairs to a ferry which took us out to our boat. We were 13 passengers on a boat built for 16.
We could not see more than 300 meters because of a dense fog and, I found out later, the captain was almost ready to cancel the whole excursion.
Our minder then assembled us in the dining room, gave a brief explanation of what we would be doing and keys to our rooms. At no time were we given any safety instructions. We were then served lunch at tables for four - I had a table with a very nice Scottish couple. Pick your tablemates with care as you will be sitting with them for all meals. The food for all meals was plentiful - six courses - but bland. I can understand this as the passengers come from a variety of culinary backgrounds.
After lunch we joined the 50 or so other junks and steamed out of the harbor for parts unknown as we couldn’t see a thing. OK - I had the “blue, sunny skies” with hundreds of islands in view picture in my mind’s eye but this was not to be. That having been said I came to enjoy the other “mystical islands rising out of the mist” picture which was my reality as viewed from the top deck. Taking a lemon... I could actually get a good view of the islands - if we sailed REAL close.
After about half an hour and giving instructions to a ship off our port bow which didn’t seem to know where they were going, we arrived at the first “element” of our tour - a limestone cave, There was one dock on the island so all 50 ships tried to get there at the same time, dock, unload their passengers and move on as fast as possible. Kudos to the ships’ captains as it was achieved with a minimum of delay. They’re done it before... I then joined hundreds of other passengers and walked up a steep stairway to the entrance of the cave. Our “guide” was supposed to guide us but I soon lost him in the crush of the crowd and instead picked up bits of the narrative from the guides of other groups I passed on the way. The guides were giving the usual cave “shtick” - “And here you can see a formation that looks like an elephant, blah, blah.” I have been to caves before. That having been said the cave was massive, well lighted and fitted with easily walk able paths. A very good job of highlighting its attractions. Just be prepared to share it with hundreds of people all shuffling along at the same time.
One thing I should mention here is the pollution of the water which was noticeable immediately after we left the harbor and throughout the whole trip. Plastic bags, garbage, unidentifiable floating objects were EVERWHERE. NOT what you would expect from a World Heritage Site. No way I would enter the water for a swim.
Then it was back on board the ship and after a half an hour we arrived at a dock for the second element of our tour: kayaking. There were two man kayaks for everyone but I chose not to kayak and hung out with the Vietnamese crew of our boat and some other boats and was taught a Vietnamese card game. They wanted to play for money but I declined. Another type of adventure.
After half an hour kayaking everyone was back on the boat and we steamed off to another cove where there were about 20 other ships anchored up. It was then time for “Happy Hour” and double up cocktails (food is included in tours but drinks are not) which in Vietnam means that if you buy two drinks you get one free. I stuck to one and then had dinner. There’s not a lot to do at night on a boat so I went off to my cabin which was a twin equipped with a working shower for a pleasant night. Slept like a baby!
The program stated that breakfast next morning was at 07.00 but I was the only person who showed up on time. It was eventually served at 8 and after breakfast we were off to the third and last element of our trip: visit to a fishing village. The “village” turned out to be a floating dock - one of maybe 20 - on which one could see various pens with live fish and crustaceans of various species floating in the water. Live! You could buy a fish and have the cook prepare it for dinner on the boat. A Malaysian woman bought a two and a half kilo fish and paid $40 - she was ripped off. I have paid $5 in Vietnam for a one kilo fish and had it barbecued at my table.
We then made for the harbor to eat lunch and end our trip when OH. MY.GOD. I suddenly knew how the English must have felt when they saw the Armada invading in 1588. Steaming towards us from the harbor were scores and scores and scores (I gave up counting at 125) of ships filled with people who were on day trips - it was 10 in the morning. I have never seen so many ships in my life and I have no doubt that they were all heading for the same destination. After lunch it was back in to the bus and off for the harrowing four hour trip back to Hanoi with the same driver who had driven us down.
I have given this “experience” a three button rating mainly because of the fact that there are just too many people and that didn’t jibe with my expectations. The actual services deserve a four button rating to Oriental Sails. While I paid $110 a quick survey of the other passengers determined that they had paid any where from $95 to $120. The food was adequate, they sailed me where I was supposed to be and provided fast (TOO fast) transportation to and from Halong Bay. They also provided the various elements of the tour they had promised. The “guide” was, however, not up to the job and did very little if any actual guiding. Luck of the draw I guess.
Written April 28, 2012
