Violet Junk Luxury Cruise Collection
Jun 2011 • Couples
We chose the two night cruise option and are very glad we did. We arrived in Hanoi and decided to go straight from the airport to Ha Long Bay, spend the night at the Novotel and join the cruise the following day. This made for a relaxing start to our trip after our 3.5 hour drive.
While waiting to join the Violet you could sit in a coffee shop withe free WiFi. This is when they take your luggage to the junk and have it waiting for your arrival. We then joined the other guests on the tender taking us out to the Violet Junk. We took a seat in the dining room and were given our room keys, a welcome drink and our iteneray. Our suite was the Dragon on the forward port top deck. This junk has only 6 cabins making it an intimate cruise.
We really liked our suite and found it very lovely as long as you did not look to close at the finish. The suite was large with a chaise lounge, desk with mini bar, in room safe (not bolted down though), spa bath and separate shower. I have to say it was one of the best views from a bathtub we have had in our travels. The decorations were indochine charm. We had no problem with hot water and had plenty of it. You could open your curtains and take in the view from bed or better yet sit on your private balcony and have the ultimate 5 star view.
The meals were quite good. We had lunch on the cruise out to our first stop of the day at a local fishing village. After our on the water tour we rejoined the Violet for cocktails and free time until dinner. You were given a few options for each course and I had the small lobster which was actually very good. During this time you could have cocktails on the top deck or get a massage. My husband and I both had a massage. It was okay, not the best, not the worst.
Next morning was an early start where you join the day boat. This is a small, newly built junk you spend the day on while the Violet goes back to port to drop off the one night guests and pick up the next lot. Once on board the Sunset we had a cooked breakfast and given a run through of the days events. We were first off to Cat Ba island for a bike ride to a village that had been there for 300 years. What good fun and really interesting. The best part of our cruise so far. Afterwards it was back for lunch and then kayaking with a crew member from the day junk. This is where you could go swimming. I will get back to this a bit later in the review. The boat is very nice, but could use a bit more shade on the top deck. Because in June the afternoon sun is very hot and very strong. There were plenty of deck chairs. But is was so hot we chose to stay inside and take advantage of the A/C.
Later in the afternoon we rejoined the Violet for before dinner cocktails. Next day was another early start for a walk up the hundred steps for a view of the bay. It is really 100 steps plus a bit of a hilly climb. So take some water with you. This is in an area they have prepared for the tourists with a pavilion, changing rooms, drinks for sale and a clean swimming area. You will also want to have a swim, as the climb is a bit steep and sweaty during the summer.
We were really happy we stayed for two nights and the time flys by and one night just does not do this area justice.
All the crew did their very best to give us good service. Yes, it could be better, but in MHO this is throughout the entire hospitality industry of Vietnam. They are on a learning curve and will only get better. The Violet is a lovely junk, the dining room on on the main deck and small sitting area on the upper deck and a beautiful area on the top deck with lounge chairs, a bar and sitting areas. Yes, the wine is expensive, we just ordered the cheaper stuff with dinner and took our own to enjoy in our cabin.
Written June 29, 2011
